 Sqac requires a connection string in order to connect to the target database. Each of the supported databases has their own distinct connection string syntax.
sqac presently supports MSSQL, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Sqlite3 and the SAP Hana database. You will need to know the db user-name / password, as well as the address:port and name of the database. Sample connection strings are provided as a reference. MSSQL Connection String cs := &quot;sqlserver://SA:my_passwd@localhost:1401?database=my_dbname&quot;  
MySQL Connection String cs := &quot;my_uname:my_passwd@tcp(192.168.1.10:3306)/my_dbname?charset=utf8&amp;parseTime=True&amp;loc=Local&quot;  
PostgreSQL Connection String cs := &quot;host=127.0.0.1 user=my_uname dbname=my_dbname sslmode=disable password=my_passwd&quot;  
Sqlite3 Connection String cs := &quot;my_db_file.sqlite&quot; // or cs = &quot;my_db_file.db&quot;  
SAP Hana Connection String cs := &quot;hdb://my_uname:my_passwd@192.168.111.45:30015&quot;

 Sqac Tag Overview Sqac table-declarations are informed by go structs with json-style struct-tags indicating column attributes. Two tags are used: &lsquo;db:&rsquo; and &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo;; the &lsquo;db:&rsquo; tag is used to declare the database column name. This is typically the snake_case conversion of the go struct field-name. The &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag is used to declare column attributes.
A list of the supported &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag attributes follows:
   sqac tag Description     &ldquo;primary_key:&rdquo; This tag is used to declare that the specified column should be used as a primary-key in the generated database table. There are a few variations in its use: &ldquo;primary_key:inc&rdquo; declares the primary-key as auto-incrementing from 0 in the database table schema: db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc&quot; &ldquo;primary_key:&rdquo; declares the primary-key as a non-auto-incrementing primary-key in the database schema: db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:&quot; &ldquo;primary_key:inc;start:90000000&rdquo; declares the primary-key as auto-incrementing starting from 900000000: db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc;start:90000000&quot; It is possible to assign the &ldquo;primary_key:&rdquo; tag to more than one column in a table&rsquo;s model declaration. The column containing the first occurrence of the tag (top-down) will be created as the actual primary-key in the database. The collection of column declarations containing the &ldquo;primary_key:&rdquo; tag will be used to create a unique index on the DB table. This is useful in cases where one is migrating data from a source system that has the concept of compound table keys. For example, the following model excerpt would result in the creation of &ldquo;depot_num&rdquo; as the table&rsquo;s primary-key as well as the creation of a unique index containing &ldquo;depot_num&rdquo;, &ldquo;depot_bay&rdquo;, &ldquo;create_date&rdquo;: DepotNum int db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc;start:90000000&quot;
DepotBay int db:&quot;depot_bay&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:&quot; CreateDate time.Time db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();index:unique&quot;
Notes: auto-incrementing primary-keys increment by 1 and must always be declared as go-type int.   &ldquo;nullable:&rdquo; This tag is used to declare that the specified column is nullable in the database. Allowed values are true or false. db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false&quot; or db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:true&quot; Notes: If this tag is not specified, the column is declared as nullable with the exception of columns declared with the &ldquo;primary_key:&rdquo; tag.   &ldquo;default: The &ldquo;default:&rdquo; tag is used to declare a default value for the column in the database table schema. Default values are used as per the implementation of the SQL DEFAULT keyword in the target DBMS. db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:YYC&quot; Notes: This tag supports the use of static values for all column-types, as well as a small set of date-time functions: &ldquo;default:now()&rdquo; / &ldquo;default:make_timestamptz(9999, 12, 31, 23, 59, 59.9)&rdquo; / &ldquo;default:eot()&rdquo;   &ldquo;index:&rdquo; Single column indexes can be declared via the &ldquo;index:&rdquo; tag. The example index declarations require only the &ldquo;index:unique / non-unique&rdquo; pair in the column&rsquo;s sqac-tag. The following column declaration results in the creation of a unique index on table column &ldquo;create_date&rdquo;: db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();index:unique&quot; A non-unique single column index for the same column is declared as follows: db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();index:non-unique&quot; Multi-column indexes can also be declared via the index tag. The following example illustrates the declaration of a non-unique two-column index containing columns &ldquo;new_column1&rdquo; and &ldquo;new_column2&rdquo;: db:&quot;new_column1&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;index:idx_depot_new_column1_new_column2&quot; db:&quot;new_column2&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:0;index:idx_depot_new_column1_new_column2&quot;    &ldquo;fkey: Foreign-keys can be declared between table columns. The following example results in the creation of a foreign-key between the table&rsquo;s &ldquo;warehouse_id&rdquo; column and reference column &ldquo;id&rdquo; in table &ldquo;warehouse&rdquo;. WarehouseID uint64 db:&quot;warehouse_id&quot; json:&quot;warehouse_id&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;fkey:warehouse(id)&quot; This example is not very clear - see the full example code excerpt in the Table Declaration Examples section.   Non-persistent column There are scenarios where model columns may not be persisted in the database. If a column is to be determined at runtime by the consuming application (for example), the following syntax may be used: NonPersistentColumn string db:&quot;non_persistent_column&quot; sqac:&quot;-&quot;

 &ldquo;nullable:&rdquo; Overview Sqac annotated go structs are used to supply the sqac runtime with the information required to create and alter tables in the database. The following examples illustrate the use of the &ldquo;nullable:&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag described in the Sqac Tag Overview section of this document.
Unless specified, most databases will create columns as nullable by default. Use the &ldquo;nullable:&rdquo; tag to explicitly declare the data requirements of fields in the source go-struct and the nullability of the corresponding columns in the database.

&ldquo;nullable:false&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;nullable:false&rdquo; to declare a column as not null in the database. If no value can be provided for a column deemed to be not nullable, consider setting a default value at the database level via the &ldquo;default:&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag, or provide the go zero-value for the field.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. // db column &quot;region&quot; will be created as NOT NULL type Depot struct { ... Region string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false&quot;` ... ... }  &ldquo;nullable:true&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;nullable:true&rdquo; to declare a column as nullable in the database. Care should be taken when deciding to create a column as nullable, as the consumer may not be expecting null values in the selected data. Note that reading a null value into a non-pointer field in the go-struct will result in an error. In the following example code the &ldquo;Region&rdquo; field has been declared as a pointer to a string (*string) rather than a string for this reason.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. // db column &quot;region&quot; will be nullable in the database type Depot struct { ... Region *string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:true&quot;` ... ... }

 &ldquo;default:&rdquo; Overview Sqac annotated go structs are used to supply the sqac runtime with the information required to create and alter tables in the database. The following examples illustrate the use of the &ldquo;default:&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag described in the Sqac Tag Overview section of this document.
Use the &ldquo;default:&rdquo; tag to explicitly declare default column values in the database table schema. The default values will be used only if no value has been provided for a defaulted column during record creation. A field with a &ldquo;default:&rdquo; tag will be defaulted at the database level if it contains a null value, or the go zero-value corresponding to the field&rsquo;s go data type.

&ldquo;default:&lt;value&gt;&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;default:&lt;value&gt;&rdquo; to declare a column&rsquo;s default value in the database table schema. Care should be taken to supply default values that correspond to the go data type of the the field/column.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. // sample default value assignments are shown type Depot struct { ... Region string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;default:AB&quot;` Efficiency float64 `db:&quot;efficiency&quot; sqac:&quot;default:99.999&quot;` Active bool `db:&quot;active&quot; sqac:&quot;default:true&quot;` ... ... }  time.Time &ldquo;default:now()&rdquo; function Most database systems offer a selection of functions to provide default time and/or timestamp values. Sqac uses UTC timestamps as discussed in section X.Y.Z for fields declared as time.Time or *time.Time. &ldquo;default:now()&rdquo; will instruct the database to use its equivalent now() function to provide a default value for the field at time of record insertion. The defaulted value will be created as a UTC timestamp.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. // field will be defaulted to current timestamp at time of record insertion type Depot struct { ... CreateDate time.Time `db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;default:now();&quot;` ... ... }  time.Time &ldquo;default:eot()&rdquo; function Most database systems offer a selection of functions to provide default date-time and/or timestamp values. Sqac uses UTC timestamps as discussed in section X.Y.Z for fields declared as time.Time or *time.Time. &ldquo;default:eot()&rdquo; will set a default value for the field based on the maximum UTC timestamp supported by the database. Typically this will be along the lines of &lsquo;9999 12 31 235959.999 UTC&rsquo;, but some databases (MySQL/MariaDB) have lower maximum timestamp values.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. // field will be defaulted to current timestamp at time of record insertion type Depot struct { ... ExpiryDate time.Time `db:&quot;expiry_date&quot; sqac:&quot;default:eot();&quot;` ... ... }

 &ldquo;index:&rdquo; Overview Sqac annotated go structs are used to supply the sqac runtime with the information required to create and alter tables in the database. The following examples illustrate the use of the &ldquo;index:&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag described in the Sqac Tag Overview section of this document.
Use the &ldquo;index:&rdquo; tag to declare unique/non-unique indexes in database table schemas. Single column and compound indexes are supported.

&ldquo;index:&lt;unique | non-unique&gt;&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;index:&rdquo; to declare a single column unique and single column non-unique index on two table fields. Creation of a unique index on a single column results in an underlying db constraint. The unique constraint prevents the insertion of records when the indexed field contains a duplicate value.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. type Depot struct { ... Region string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;default:AB;index:non-unique&quot;` // non-unique index AccountNum int `db:&quot;account_num&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;index:unique&quot;` // unique index ... ... }  &ldquo;index:&rdquo; compound example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;index:&rdquo; to declare a multi-column non-unique index using two table fields. As of this writing, sqac does not support the creation of a unique compound index through the &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag model declarations.
Conventionally the compound index should be named as shown in the example below.
idx_&lt;table_name&gt;_&lt;field_name1&gt;_&lt;field_name2&gt;_&lt;field_namen&gt;
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. type Depot struct { ... Country string `db:&quot;country&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:CA;index:idx_depot_country_province&quot;` Province string `db:&quot;province&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:AB;index:idx_depot_country_province&quot;` ... ... }

 &ldquo;constraint:&lt;value&gt;&rdquo; Overview Sqac annotated go structs are used to supply the sqac runtime with the information required to create and alter tables in the database. The following examples illustrate the use of the &ldquo;constraint:&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag described in the Sqac Tag Overview section of this document.
The &ldquo;constraint:&rdquo; tag is presently only used to declare unique constraints on single columns. It would be relatively simple to add support for any desired database constraint however.

&ldquo;constraint:unique&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;constraint:&rdquo; to declare a unique column constraint. Creation of a unique constraint on a single column results in an underlying db constraint, but does not necessarily create an index on the constrained column. Check the target db documentation for details.
If a column has been declared with a single-column index, the &ldquo;constraint:unique&rdquo; tag is redundant. If a column has been declared with unique constraint, it may still be included in a compound &ldquo;index:&rdquo; declaration.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. type Depot struct { ... AccountNum int `db:&quot;account_num&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;constraint:unique&quot;` // unique constraint ... ... }

 non-persistent tag Overview Sqac annotated go structs are used to supply the sqac runtime with the information required to create and alter tables in the database. The following examples illustrate the use of the &ldquo;-&rdquo; &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag described in the Sqac Tag Overview section of this document.
The &ldquo;-&rdquo; tag is used to declare a field in the source go struct as being non-persistent (not present) in the database table schema. Non-persistent fields are useful for values that are to be determined client-side, or for input fields that should not be saved.

&rdquo;-&rdquo; example The following example illustrates the use of &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tag &ldquo;-&rdquo; to declare a go struct field as non-persistent in the database.
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. type Depot struct { ... Password string `db:&quot;password&quot; sqac:&quot;-&quot;` // column will not be created in the database ... ... }


PublicDB.CreateTables(i &hellip;interface{}) error The CreateTables method is used to create one or more tables in the target database. CreateTables accepts one or more go struct definitions that have been annotated with &ldquo;sqac:&rdquo; tags and uses the provided information to create new tables in the database.
Errors encountered during table creation are returned to the caller immediately. This may result in the incomplete processing of the tables contained in parameter i &hellip;interface{}. CreateTables Example // Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation. type Depot struct { DepotNum int `db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc&quot;` CreateDate time.Time `db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();&quot;` Country string `db:&quot;country&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:CA&quot;` Province string `db:&quot;province&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:AB&quot;` Region string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:YYC&quot;` Population int `db:&quot;population&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:0;index:non-unique&quot;` }  The struct shown above can be used by sqac to create a table named &ldquo;depot&rdquo; in the target database. In order to call the PublicDB.CreateTables() method, an instance of PublicDB must be created and connected to the database. A small sample program illustrating the creation of table &ldquo;depot&rdquo; follows:
package main import ( &quot;log&quot; &quot;github.com/1414C/sqac&quot; _ &quot;github.com/SAP/go-hdb/driver&quot; _ &quot;github.com/denisenkom/go-mssqldb&quot; _ &quot;github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql&quot; _ &quot;github.com/lib/pq&quot; _ &quot;github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3&quot; ) func main() { var ( Handle sqac.PublicDB ) // Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation type Depot struct { DepotNum int `db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc&quot;` CreateDate time.Time `db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();&quot;` Country string `db:&quot;country&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:CA&quot;` Province string `db:&quot;province&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:AB&quot;` Region string `db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:YYC&quot;` Population int `db:&quot;population&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:0;index:non-unique&quot;` } // Create a PublicDB instance to connect to the test sqlite db Handle = sqac.Create(&quot;sqlite&quot;, false, false, &quot;testdb.sqlite&quot;) // Create a new table in the database err := Handle.CreateTables(Depot{}) if err != nil { log.Errorf(&quot;%s&quot;, err.Error()) } // Close the connection Handle.Close() }


PublicDB.GetEntity(ent interface{}) error The GetEntity method is part of sqac&rsquo;s CRUD API and is used to retrieve an existing row of the specified entity from it&rsquo;s related database table. Structs annotated with &lsquo;sqac:&rsquo; tags are colloquially known as sqac entities, hence the parameter name &lsquo;ent&rsquo;.
The ent parameter must be a pointer to a go struct of the sqac table declaration in which the primary-key fields have been populated. The GetEntity method can be thought of as a fully-keyed SELECT SINGLE statement. If an error is encountered, it will be returned to the caller.
PublicDB.GetEntitiesCP is a more flexible and useful method.
CRUD GetEntity Example The following example illustrates the deletion of an existing record (entity) from database table &ldquo;depot&rdquo;.
```golang package main
import ( &ldquo;log&rdquo;
&ldquo;github.com/1414C/sqac&rdquo; _ &ldquo;github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3&rdquo; )
func main() {
var ( Handle sqac.PublicDB )
// Declare a struct to be used as the source for table creation type Depot struct { DepotNum int db:&quot;depot_num&quot; sqac:&quot;primary_key:inc&quot; CreateDate time.Time db:&quot;create_date&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:now();&quot; Country string db:&quot;country&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:CA&quot; Province string db:&quot;province&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:AB&quot; Region string db:&quot;region&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:YYC&quot; Population int db:&quot;population&quot; sqac:&quot;nullable:false;default:0;index:non-unique&quot; }
// Create a PublicDB instance to connect to the test sqlite db Handle = sqac.Create(&ldquo;sqlite&rdquo;, false, false, &ldquo;testdb.sqlite&rdquo;)
// Create a new table in the database err := Handle.DestructiveResetTables(Depot{}) if err != nil { log.Errorf(&ldquo;%s&rdquo;, err.Error()) }
// Insert a new record into table &ldquo;depot&rdquo; var depotRecord = Depot{ Country: &ldquo;CA&rdquo;, Province: &ldquo;BC&rdquo;, Region: &ldquo;YVR&rdquo;, Population: 2500000, }
err = Handle.Create(&amp;depotRecord) if err != nil { log.Errorf(err.Error()) } else { log.Println(&ldquo;New record: &ldquo;, depotRecord) }
// Retrieve the existing record using the fully populated depotRecord&rsquo;s primary-key value var readRecord = Depot{ DepotNum: depotRecord.DepotNum, } err = Handle.GetEntity(&amp;readRecord) if err != nil { log.Errorf(err.Error()) } else { log.Println(&ldquo;Retrieved record: &ldquo;,readRecord) }
// Close the connection Handle.Close() }


sqac.IndexInfo IndexInfo is used by sqac to provide information to the PublicDB.CreateIndex method regarding the table name, uniqueness and columns to be included in a new database index.
// IndexInfo contains index definitions as read from the sqac:&quot;index&quot; tags type IndexInfo struct { TableName string Unique bool IndexFields []string }  
sqac.GetParam GetParam defines a common structure for CRUD GET parameters and is used in the PublicDB.GetEntitiesCP method.
type GetParam struct { FieldName string // database column name Operand string // operand for parameter (ie. ==, !=, &lt; etc.) ParamValue interface{} // parameter value NextOperator string // deprecated - do not use }
